The King Faisal Mosque in Sharjah's Al Soor area is among the most recognisable landmarks of the emirate. 
At 12,000 square metres, it is the biggest mosque in Sharjah. It was opened in 1987 and can accommodate 15,000 people at a time. 
There are separate prayer rooms for men and women and the mosque has an Islamic library with more than 7,000 books.

Emirates and Frontier Economics, a leading European consultancy, released today the results of a socio-economic impact study that measures Emirates' contribution to the European economy. Frontier estimates that Emirates' operations, including the catalytic impact of the 220 unique connections it offers, supported 85,100 jobs across the EU in 2013-14, equivalent to Euro 6.8 billion GDP, or 0.05 per cent of the total EU GDP. In addition, Emirates' Airbus A380 deliveries for the same period supported 41,000 jobs, equivalent to Euro 3.4 billion GDP.

status_message: This tiny emirate enjoys the best of both worlds. There's something for those who prefer to transit, or others who like to linger. Modern habitats appear to have taken over the desert environment and you get the feeling you are never alone here. The roads in Ajman City are generally packed with those making trips to Dubai or Sharjah for work and pleasure. It can be challenging with motorists weaving in and out of traffic. Residents find the rents affordable, the corniche welcoming on holidays, if you wish to simply gaze at the breakers in Arabian Gulf, not to forget the rising skyline which is home to some fine dining areas and niche residences. It can even look pretty on a night out. Though small in size, Ajman has the ability to punch above its weight. It makes the most of its resources and fledgling entrepreneurial spirit. The Ajman Port and Free Zone have rode on opportunities that have come their way with a range of businesses being set up here. The emirate is a thriving textile and manufacturing hub, competing with the most established ones in other areas of the UAE. Real estate is recovering after a slump and optimism is back. Ajman never ceases to surprise.
link_name: Countdown to UAE National Day: Ajman

status_message: From the air you breathe to the food you eat and the greenery you enjoy, there is hardly anything more that the municipal services in the city can offer. It is now the turn of the residents of this vibrant city to tell the world how much they love it. The civic body has therefore unveiled a channel for residents to open up their hearts.  The #happydubai initiative encourages people to express their happiness about Dubai through pictures and proclamations. Miles and miles of pristine beaches, beautiful gardens, 645 heritage buildings lovingly preserved, over 8,500 eating out places ... these are just a few of things that make  people in Dubai happy. Khaleej Times captures some of the posts on Twitter and Instagram from those who were the first to join the #happydubai initiative.
link_name: #happydubai: Initiative to express Dubai experience via pictures

The earlier the better ... for learning certain skills, at least. Swimming is one such skill that could be acquired even before one learns to walk or talk. And that could be as early as four months. The Active Sports Academy is one institution that helps little ones achieve this in Dubai.

If worried parents feared that their child would drown when placed in the water, swimming instructor for babies, Louise, vouches that they won't. In fact, doing so with proper assistance from parents will help the babies — they will lose the fear of water, and it aids the development of balance, coordination and strength. They also love to splash around.

By two years, most of them would have learnt to swim. It could help bring down incidents of drowning of children in pools, as have happened in the emirates recently.

The academy, sponsored by Mothercare, runs swimming lessons for different age groups of children beginning from four to 12 months under a programme called Water Babies. KT photographer Juidin Bernarrd, who attended sessions for three age groups, captures the fleeting moments.

status_message: Life's like that...

Date palms get a haircut: As summer gives way to winter, date palms that dot roadsides and parks in the UAE also need to dress up for the season. The trees undergo pruning during this season to remove dead and dying fronds, which help them avoid infestations of insects, cockroaches, scorpions, spiders and rats. The pruning is also the time for the final harvest of the season's dates. These steps help the trees get fresh green leaves and stronger stems, fronds and fruit. KT lensman Mukesh Kamal takes us through the process of pruning at Al Badia Golf Club in Dubai Festival City.

UAE LEADERS RECEIVE KUWAIT AMIR 
The President, His Highness Shaikh Khalifa bin Zayed Al Nahyan, on Saturday received the Amir of Kuwait, His Highness Shaikh Sabah Al Ahmad Al Sabah in Jasyora, Al Ain, in the presence of His Highness Shaikh Mohammed bin Rashid Al Maktoum, Vice-President and Prime Minister of the UAE and Ruler of Dubai. Shaikh Khalifa and Shaikh Sabah discussed the bilateral relations and ways to promote them in various spheres. They also discussed recent regional and international developments and matters of common concern. The President hosted a luncheon in honour of the the Kuwaiti leader and his entourage. Shaikh Sabah, who concluded his visit in the afternoon, expressed his appreciation for Shaikh Khalifa's hospitality and warm welcome. — Wam

On September 30, Cafe racers, bobbers, flat trackers, classics, retros and quirky motorcycles and their owners across the globe united for a day of distinguished nonsense. They rode the world for no reason other than being distinguished. The Dubai edition of the Distinguished Gentlemen's Ride was rolled out by the RED motorcycle club. RED stands for Righteous Eggheads Dubai — a motorcycle club that began as a bunch of Royal Enfield owners and enthusiasts in Dubai. Registered in 2011 as the Royal Enfield Dubai Motorcycle Club, it has grown to become a gathering of like-minded motorcyclists who love to ride the open, winding roads and enjoy lip-smacking eggrolls on weekends chased down by a cup of chai. Not necessarily in that order!They took to the streets for a night of immature stupidity and fun while wearing a suit. And KT photographer, Shihab,was there to capture it. "The idea is to eventually run an annual worldwide event when gentlemen don their suits and ride their cafe racers and classic motorcycles through town spreading merriment along the way," said one of the riders. It is a day where no matter what your work/social/life status may be, everyone is equally distinguished.

status_message: Since its relaunch in October 2010, RAK Airways, one of the flagship carriers of the UAE, has worked on building passenger numbers, filling 250,000 seats in 2011, while gradually expanding its destination network to Africa, The Middle East and Asia. On October 3, Abu Dhabi Airports Company welcomed the inaugural arrival of the RAK Airways flight at the Abu Dhabi International Airport, marking the first domestic flight operated by the airline. The airline's plan is to land in Abu Dhabi, bringing the Capital closer to the residents of Ras Al Khaimah and the Northern Emirates. RAK Airways has launched four direct flights a week between the Capital and Ras Al Khaimah, and the flight duration is 20 minutes. KT photographer Juidin Bernarrd shares his experience on the inaugural flight. After flying over the landmarks of Dubai, and just about 15 minutes into the flight, the captain of the 320 Airbus announced the flight's landing at the Abu Dhabi airport and we passengers got off to a rousing welcome, says Juidin.

From furniture to DVDs and clothes to electrical equipment, the Dubai Flea Market is a treasure trove of bargains. Taking place at Al Safa Hall, the market boasts of hundreds of stalls stocking a wide range of used goods. Not only is it a great place to find second-hand products, it also features stalls selling unique handmade items. The market also offers the chance to raise money for a good cause, with many of the sellers donating the proceeds to charity.A traditional flea market takes place outdoors, as does the Dubai Flea Market during cooler months. But as summer intensifies, the market moves into the air-conditioned comfort of Al Safa Hall.From June to September, the market takes place on the first and third Friday of every month from 3 to 8pm. In October, it moves outdoors, at Al Safa Park.There is excitement and chaos as vendors try to sell their products and buyers haggle for the best possible price. The enthusiasm is infectious, says KT photographer Shihab.

PRINCESS TOWER SETS GUINNESS RECORD

Guinness World Records has officially recognised Tameer's Princess Tower as the world's tallest residential building, towering over the Dubai Marina skyline at 414m from base to tip. 
The prestigious Dubai Marina development stands a staggering 107 storeys tall and encompasses six basement floors, one ground floor, 100 above-ground levels and eight retail stores. The tower occupies a land area of 37,410 square feet, housing 763 luxury apartments, including one, two, three and four bedroom apartments in addition to penthouse apartments overlooking the Palm Jumeirah.

Summer has well and truly arrived, with the temperature and humidity climbing by the day. Stepping out of the house or the car has become unthinkable. But there is no way out. The wise move would be to be prepared. Make sure to drink lots and lots of water, and to carry the umbrella if you have to walk up to the Metro. Khaleej times's photographer Rahul Gajjar says his heart goes out to the delivery men and the workers at construction sites who bear the brunt of the heat. status_message:
Khaleej Times backs global manhunt for Joseph Kony

Joseph Kony was born in 1961 as an Acholi tribal and his Lords Liberation Army (LRA) stronghold covers the borders of Uganda,
the Congo and southern Sudan.

Kony is known to have raided villages, kidnapped children as young as eight and put them into uniform as child soldiers often forcing them to murder their own parents. And other family members. He has abducted girls and converted them at gunpoint into sex slaves.

Russell's film estimates the number of children at around 30,000; It's reported elsewhere to be as high as 70,000. Because of him over 2 million people have been displaced and they still live in fear.

According to Wikipedia the LRA is a militant group with a extreme religious ideology. "They are known for the extreme atrocities they commit against civilians, including murder, mutilations, rape, and in some accounts even cannibalism."
